name: 1,3-diphenylisobenzofuran
Reason: The basic unit to consider is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. Each phenyl group adds to this value since they contribute to an increase in molecular weight and van der Waals forces. The addition of two more phenyl groups (considering the ones not in the furan ring system) to benzene might increase the melting point significantly. For each phenyl group, considering a similar effect as toluene, we could estimate an increase of about 30 degrees Celsius. The furan ring and its connection to the benzene rings introduce additional rigidity to the structure and possible pi-stacking interactions that would also increase the melting point. Given the complexity of predicting the interaction of the furan ring, a conservative estimate for the additional furan and its interactions could be an additional 20 degrees Celsius. Combining the effects, the prediction would be an increase of 5.5 + (2 * 30) + 20 degrees Celsius.
